oakcurric:unit-3557
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Product analysis: encouraging healthy lifestyles"@en ;
  curric:slug "product-analysis-encouraging-healthy-lifestyles" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will analyse products to identify features in the products. They will also
  identify the materials, material properties and manufacturing processes used to create the
  products. They will conduct functional tests to collect and analyse data to inform design
  decisions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Knowledge of product analysis (critiquing products, materials and
  manufacturing processes) is essential for effective designing. This unit builds upon previous
  units such as Year 9 'Developments in New Materials', in which pupils' learn about different
  materials and their categories. Knowledge within this unit progresses to specific examples
  and how this knowledge can inform design decisions. This lays the foundations for pupils to
  justify their decisions when creating ideas as part of iterative design, Non-Examined
  Assessment and later units such as Core Principles.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3557-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3557-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3557-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3557-4 ;
  curric:id "3557"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.920393Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    oakcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oakcurric:thread-user-centred-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate .

oakcurric:unit-3600
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Iterative design: Nature"@en ;
  curric:slug "iterative-design-nature" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils learn about biomimicry and innovation. They will learn how to use sources
  of inspiration to create a range of ideas for a product encouraging children to grow
  vegetables. The pupils will develop ideas and manufacture a prototype. Variation allows
  for different material outcomes."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Knowledge of the sources of inspiration and the skills to use these to
  inform decisions is an important part of iterative design. Pupils have learnt about different
  sources of inspiration in the Year 9 'Circular Economy' unit and the Year 10 'Product
  analysis: Encouraging healthy lifestyle' unit. This unit will enable pupils to use
  inspiration sources which suit the context and client, which will prepare pupils for future
  interative design and the Non-Examined Assessment.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3600-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3600-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3600-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3600-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3600-5 ;
  curric:id "3600"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.020530Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    oakcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-user-centred-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-materials ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate ,
    oakcurric:thread-manufacture .

oakcurric:unit-3601
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Investigate and research: High profile event"@en ;
  curric:slug "investigate-and-research-high-profile-event" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will identify a client and investigate the client's needs and wants. They
  will use and develop different research techniques. They will learn about the economic
  viability of designs to design a product for a high-profile event."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Knowledge of different research methods and the techniques to analyse the
  data collected is important for effective design. Pupils have knowledge of research from
  prior units, such as the Year 8 'Ergonomic controllers' and the Year 9 ' New parents'. The
  knowledge of an increasing range of research strategies learnt here will prepare pupils for
  independent selection of the most appropriate methods in subsequent iterative design units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3601-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3601-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3601-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3601-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3601-5 ;
  curric:id "3601"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.689608Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    oakcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-4 .

oakcurric:unit-3599
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Systems approach to design: Sustainable Futures"@en ;
  curric:slug "systems-approach-to-design-sustainable-futures" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils will develop knowledge of electronic components and a systems approach to
  designing. They will learn about different components and use these to build and test
  circuits for different purposes. They will design a system to control a greenhouse
  environment, considering the different variables."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Knowledge of integrating electronic and control systems into products is
  essential for effective design. By integrating more variables, this unit builds upon the
  previous unit in Year 9, 'Functional prototypes: wearable technology'. Computer-aided design
  is key learning in this unit, which develops the knowledge from the Year 7 'Prototypes with
  mechanisms: promotional displays' unit by including electronics, control, and mechanisms.
  This lays the foundations for pupils to design integrated systems within subsequent iterative
  design units and the Non-Examined Assessment.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3599-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3599-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3599-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3599-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3599-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3599-6 ;
  curric:id "3599"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.069393Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    oakcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate .

oakcurric:unit-3603
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Inclusive Design: Mental Health and Wellbeing"@en ;
  curric:slug "inclusive-design-an-ageing-population" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores inclusive design with a focus on mental health and wellbeing.
  Students research user needs, generate ideas, and prototype solutions, developing empathy,
  creativity, and problem-solving while considering feasibility and real-world impact."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Knowledge of critiquing products, materials and manufacturing processes is
  essential for effective designing. This unit builds upon the previous unit in Year 10
  'Product analysis: Encouraging healthy lifestyles', in which pupils learn how to critique
  different products, materials and processes. Knowledge lays the foundations for pupils to
  justify their decisions when creating ideas as part of iterative designing and the later Year
  11 unit 'Core principles'.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3603-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3603-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3603-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3603-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3603-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3603-6 ;
  curric:id "3603"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.118929Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    oakcurric:scheme-design-and-technology-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-user-centred-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-design ,
    oakcurric:thread-critique-and-evaluate .

